00:10:03,239 --> 00:10:05,440
of subagents one more time.

267
00:10:05,440 --> 00:10:08,599
So when you're thinking about using subagents

268
00:10:08,599 --> 00:10:11,080
as the way to add functionality

269
00:10:11,080 --> 00:10:13,760
versus things like skills and commands,

270
00:10:13,760 --> 00:10:14,919
remember, first of all,

271
00:10:14,919 --> 00:10:18,119
it allows you to do more in parallel at the same time.

272
00:10:18,119 --> 00:10:20,679
You can have multiple subagents working together.

273
00:10:20,679 --> 00:10:22,320
They can be self-corrective.

274
00:10:22,320 --> 00:10:24,640
They can not only allow you to do more at once,

275
00:10:24,640 --> 00:10:26,679
but they can also sort of have a negative feedback

276
00:10:26,679 --> 00:10:29,640
that they keep you more under control, doing a bit less.

277
00:10:29,640 --> 00:10:31,840
They can be very efficient for your context.

278
00:10:31,840 --> 00:10:34,280
It's usually the first reason you use subagents

279
00:10:34,280 --> 00:10:37,000
is because you pull stuff off the main context

280
00:10:37,000 --> 00:10:38,320
for Claude Code,

281
00:10:38,320 --> 00:10:40,280
and they can be focused on one task

282
00:10:40,280 --> 00:10:42,599
that allows you to perfect the prompting,

283
00:10:42,599 --> 00:10:45,679
perfect the task at hand, do one thing really well,

284
00:10:45,679 --> 00:10:47,719
and be really good at it,

285
00:10:47,719 --> 00:10:50,039
keeping, again, that kind of context

286
00:10:50,039 --> 00:10:52,320
off your main Claude Code.

287
00:10:52,320 --> 00:10:55,359
But with these strengths come a few drawbacks.

288
00:10:55,359 --> 00:10:58,799
So any time you've got this kind of ability

289
00:10:58,799 --> 00:11:00,640
to delegate to some other process,

290
00:11:00,640 --> 00:11:02,719
you're adding more moving parts.

291
00:11:02,719 --> 00:11:04,880
There's more complexity in your system,

292
00:11:04,880 --> 00:11:06,559
which means that more things can go wrong

293
00:11:06,559 --> 00:11:09,719
in a mysterious way that's harder to track down.

294
00:11:09,719 --> 00:11:12,239
There are what I call boundary issues

295
00:11:12,239 --> 00:11:14,359
or problems at the interfaces

296
00:11:14,359 --> 00:11:16,919
between your subagent and your main agent

297
00:11:16,919 --> 00:11:18,799
that can result in mistakes.

298
00:11:18,799 --> 00:11:21,840
You can have this amplification of problems

299
00:11:21,840 --> 00:11:23,400
when you divvy up the task.

300
00:11:23,400 --> 00:11:24,799
Something can go a bit wrong,

301
00:11:24,799 --> 00:11:26,840
and then agents go off in different directions,

302
00:11:26,840 --> 00:11:28,679
and it gets more and more wrong

303
00:11:28,679 --> 00:11:30,840
in a way that's kind of hard to recover,

304
00:11:30,840 --> 00:11:32,640
compounding errors.

305
00:11:33,640 --> 00:11:35,640
Whilst subagents are sometimes touted

306
00:11:35,640 --> 00:11:37,119
as a way to save money

307
00:11:37,119 --> 00:11:39,159
because you can use a cheaper model

308
00:11:39,159 --> 00:11:41,080
to do some of your processing,

309
00:11:41,080 --> 00:11:43,640
they can also be a way that money can add up

310
00:11:43,640 --> 00:11:45,239
because you're just doing a lot more.

311
00:11:45,239 --> 00:11:46,679
You've got more churn,

312
00:11:46,679 --> 00:11:47,520
particularly if you've got

313
00:11:47,520 --> 00:11:49,000
the sort of self-correcting agents

314
00:11:49,000 --> 00:11:50,559
that are doing code reviews,

315
00:11:50,559 --> 00:11:51,880
doing document reviews,

316
00:11:51,880 --> 00:11:53,200
coming back for feedback.

317
00:11:53,200 --> 00:11:54,479
So more is going on.

318
00:11:54,479 --> 00:11:57,080
Hopefully that results in better outcomes,

319
00:11:57,080 --> 00:11:59,080
but it might also mean that ultimately

320
00:11:59,080 --> 00:12:00,919
you spend more getting there.

321
00:12:00,919 --> 00:12:02,159
So look, needless to say,

322
00:12:02,200 --> 00:12:03,280
we're going to have more time

323
00:12:03,280 --> 00:12:04,359
to talk about this.

324
00:12:04,359 --> 00:12:05,919
I don't want to overwhelm you

325
00:12:05,919 --> 00:12:07,799
with these bits and pieces.

326
